{
  "text": "All animals were anesthetized with 3%-5% of sevoflurane and 1 l/min of oxygen and were injected intravenously in the tail with activity of about 30 and 50 MBq, respectively. PET acquisitions of 20 minutes were performed after an uptake time depending on the radiotracer. The uptake was of about one hour for 18 F-FDG and 18 F-NaF studies, and about 30 minutes for 68 Ga-chloride acquisitions. The 11 C-acetate images were acquired immediately after the injection. A CT scan of 6 minutes was then performed for each animal after PET acquisition. PET and CT images were coregistered in order to perform AC. The segmentation process was applied on each PET image, and the SE-AC method was tested on animals studied with different radiopharmaceuticals. In order to compare the two methods, CT-AC was performed for each image as well. We analyzed all the images performing profiles across an axial slice of a particular anatomical region related to the radiotracer used and calculating the mean value in the anatomical ROI. Thus, we calculated the recovery values according to [CITATION_1] and evaluated the segmentation-based AC method on heart, spinal column, liver, and kidneys using 18 F-FDG, 18 F-NaF, 11 C-acetate, and 68 Ga-chloride, respectively.",
  "citation_candidates": [
